{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"324ac3b5-5d88-471c-b4b8-e6e1113ad039","content":"There's no repo-specific documentation on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` (it's a CoreCLR tool), so you rely on **macOS's built-in crash reporting**:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes them to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** via the shell before running your app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n4. **If `/cores` is missing or empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps and that the `/cores` directory exists with appropriate permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **Symbolicate the Apple crash log** — if you built with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`), the `.crash`/`.ips` file's addresses can be resolved with `atos`:\n   ```bash\n   atos -o /path/to/your/app -l <load_address> <crash_address>\n   ```\n\n**Key takeaway:** Set `ulimit -c unlimited` *before* the crash, then load the core file in `lldb`. Apple's Diagnostic Reports directory is your fallback if you forgot.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aef26bb3-f29b-4d99-b6a3-1ed23b564fad","outputTokens":429,"requestId":"A0D1:2EA4C2:95FDED:B89AB5:6A013758"},"id":"a126496b-cdc9-4238-a6c1-ca1c04392d26","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:56:52.287Z","parentId":"7e4d7816-2840-4d8a-8ae5-3c830b0f5348"}
